possession associated with South African neoliberalism perpetuate relations of spatial exclusion, poverty, and racism. As Makhulu demonstrates, the efforts of black Capetonians to establish claims to a place in the city not only decisively reshaped Cape Town's geography but changed the course of history.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aApartheidzSouth AfricazCape Town. 0aSquatter settlementszSouth AfricazCape TownxHistoryy20th century. 0aSquatters - Political activity - South Africa - Cape Town. 0aSquattersxPolitical activityzSouth AfricazCape Town. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375111zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375111.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles